-- French Stocks Advance: Alstom, Axa, Renault, Saint-Gobain, Technip Climb
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-14T16:28:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/french-stocks-advance-alstom-axa-michelin-renault-saint-gobain-climb.html

          
          
             France’s  CAC 40 Index  rallied 70.52,
or 2 percent, to 3,626.04, a fourth day of gains.  The SBF 120
Index  climbed 1.9 percent.  
 The following shares rose or fell in Paris. Stock symbols
are in parentheses.  
 Alstom SA  (ALO FP) advanced 5.9 percent to 39.79 euros,
gaining for a fourth day. Shares of the world’s third-largest
power-equipment maker were added to BofA Merrill Lynch Global
Research’s “Europe 1” list.  
 ArcelorMittal  (MT NA) rallied 5.6 percent to 24.88 euros,
its highest level in two weeks. The world’s biggest steelmaker
was raised to “buy” from “hold” at Collins Stewart Plc.  
 Axa SA  (CS FP) climbed 3.7 percent to 13.6 euros,
increasing for a fourth day. Europe’s second-biggest insurer
said the price for the sale of part of its U.K. life insurance
unit to Resolution Ltd. would be about 3.3 billion euros ($4
billion).  
 Club Mediterranee SA  (CU FP) surged 9.1 percent to 13.75
euros, extending a four-day gain. Fosun International Ltd. of
China bought a 7.1 percent stake in the company. Oddo Securities
raised its recommendation on the shares to “buy” from “add.”  
 Faurecia SA  (EO FP) rallied 5 percent to 14.83 euros,
gaining for a fourth day. Europe’s largest maker of automotive
interiors forecast a 72 percent increase in sales by 2014 as the
company expands abroad and pursues takeovers.  
 Ipsen SA  (IPN FP) sank 5.2 percent to 31.9 euros after a
Piper Jaffray Ltd. analyst said the experimental taspoglutide
diabetes drug that the company is developing with Roche Holding
AG may cause more nausea than a competing medicine. The analyst
cited abstracts of studies to be presented this month at the
American Diabetes Association meeting. The analyst, Sam Fazeli,
cut Ipsen’s stock to “underweight” from “overweight.”  
 Renault SA  (RNO FP) rose 2.7 percent to 31.45 euros,
gaining for a fourth day. France’s second-biggest carmaker,
which received 3 billion euros in state loans as part of
France’s aid package for the country’s auto industry, aims to
start repaying at least 500 million euros this year, Chief
Executive Officer  Carlos Ghosn  told Europe 1 radio in an
interview.  
 Cie. de Saint-Gobain SA  (SGO FP) increased 2.5 percent to
33.67 euros, climbing for a third day. Qatari Diar, a unit of
the country’s sovereign wealth fund, plans to take a stake in
Saint-Gobain, La Lettre de L’Expansion reported, without citing
anyone. The weekly newsletter didn’t give any indication of the
size of the planned investment.  
 Technip SA  (TEC FP), Europe’s second-largest oilfield-
services provider, jumped 4.3 percent to 51.82 euros.  Vallourec
SA  (VK FP), a producer of steel pipes for the oil and gas
industry, climbed 3.1 percent to 147.4 euros. Crude oil advanced
in New York to trade above $75 on speculation growth in the U.S.
economy will boost fuel demand from the world’s biggest energy
consumer.  
